    explanationBeginner: "Caliber is the size of the bullet and the barrel. It’s given in inches (like .308) or millimetres (like 7.62 mm). The same size can have different names: .308 Winchester and 7.62×51 mm are the same diameter. You must use ammunition that matches your rifle’s caliber.",
    explanationIntermediate: "Caliber denotes bore or bullet diameter. Inch calibers (e.g. .223, .308) are nominal; actual bore and groove dimensions can differ. Metric designations (e.g. 7.62 mm, 6.5 mm) are common in Europe. Cartridge names often include caliber (e.g. .308 Winchester, 6.5 Creedmoor). In the app, caliber is part of the rifle profile and is used for display and for ensuring consistency with bullet diameter in ballistic calculations.",
    explanationExpert: "Caliber can mean bore diameter (land-to-land), groove diameter (groove-to-groove), or bullet diameter; the latter is typically 0.001–0.003 in larger than groove. Nominal designations (.308, 7.62 mm) are not always identical: .308 Win and 7.62 NATO share dimensions but pressure specs differ. Twist rate and bullet length must suit the caliber for stability (e.g. Greenhill). The ballistic solver uses caliber only implicitly via bullet weight and BC; the primary role in the app is rifle identification and compatibility checks.",
