    explanationExpert: "1 radian = 1000 mrad; at range R, 1 mrad subtends R/1000 linear units (e.g. 1 m at 1000 m, 10 cm at 100 m). The range formula R = (h × 1000) / θ_mrad assumes flat fire and that θ is the angle subtended by the target; for FFP scopes the reticle directly gives θ in mrad. True mrad is 1000/(2π) ≈ 159.15 per 360°; some scopes use “mil” = 1/6400 circle (shooters’ mil), a 0.97% error. Consistency between reticle and turret (true vs shooters’ mil) matters for long-range work. The app uses 1 mrad = 1 m at 1000 m.",
